Top 100 México is a record chart which accounts for sixty percent of the albums sold in Mexico. The chart has the support of major record distributors in Mexico and is issued by the Mexican Association of Producers of Phonograms and Videograms, A.C.(Asociación Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas) since 2005 on a weekly basis.<ref name="amp">cite web|title=¿Qué Es El Top 100 Mexico? |url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/top100.php?item=menuTop100&contenido=que_es |language=Spanish |accessdate=April 12, 2011 |publisher=Asociación Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319194345/http://www.amprofon.com.mx/top100.php?item=menuTop100&contenido=que_es |archivedate=March 19, 2011 </ref> The Top 100 México contains over 100 titles sold in the country, with separate charts that include 20 albums for popular music genres, such as Norteño (music)|norteño, Banda music|banda and ranchera, Spanish language|Spanish, and English language albums.<ref name="amp"/>

In 2005, the best-selling album in Mexico was the Rebelde (album)|soundtrack for the TV series ''Rebelde (Mexican telenovela)|Rebelde'', recorded by the lead cast members, who eventually formed the band RBD;<ref name="RBD">cite web|title=RBD – Biography |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/rbd-p690724/biography |accessdate=April 15, 2011 |first=Jason |last=Birchmeier |work=Allmusic  |publisher=Rovi Corporation</ref> in the United States the album sold 416,000 copies and was named the Pop Album of the Year at the Billboard Latin Music Awards.<ref name="RBD2">cite web|title=Billboard Bits: Tony Bennett, Jack Black, RBD |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57029/billboard-bits-tony-bennett-jack-black-rbd |accessdate=April 15, 2011 |first=Clover |last=Hope |publisher=Billboard (magazine)|Billboard</ref> ''La Voz de un Ángel'' by Yuridia was the number-one selling album of 2006 (also ranked at number 5 in 2005 and 52 in 2007),<ref name="AMP-2005"/><ref name="AMP-2006"/><ref name="AMP-2007"/> and the album eventually received a diamond certification in the country, the first since 1996 when performer Luis Miguel achieved that feat.<ref name="Yuridia">cite web|title=Yuridia – Biography |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/yuridia-p749687/biography |accessdate=April 15, 2011 |first=Evan C. |last=Gutierrez |work=Allmusic  |publisher=Rovi Corporation</ref> ''Papito (album)|Papito'' by Spanish performer Miguel Bosé was the best-selling album of 2007, received the Premios Oye!|Oye! Award for Album of the Year and earned four Latin Grammy Awards of 2007|Latin Grammy Award nominations.<ref name="Bose">cite web|title="Papito" el mejor álbum del año |url=http://www.los40.com.co/nota.aspx?id=471150 |date=August 24, 2007 |accessdate=April 18, 2011 |language=Spanish |publisher=Los40.com </ref>

''Para Siempre'', the 79th studio album released by Vicente Fernández was the number-one album of 2008 in Mexico and the best-selling Regional-Mexican album of the decade 2000-2009 in the United States.<ref name="V-Fernandez">cite web|title=Best of the 2000s – Regional Mexican Albums |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts-decade-end#/charts-decade-end/regional-mexican-albums?year=2009 |accessdate=April 18, 2011 |publisher=Billboard</ref> Mexican band Camila (band)|Camila earned a gold certificacion in Mexico the day of the release of their second studio album ''Dejarte de Amar'', which ended 2010 as the best-selling recording in the country.<ref name="Camila">cite web|title=Camila recibe Disco de Oro por nuevo material |url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/657802.html |date=February 10, 2011 |accessdate=April 18, 2011 |language=Spanish |publisher=El Universal </ref> Since May 2013, some positions of the chart are published in the official Twitter account of AMPROFON including the number one position.<ref>cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Amprofon |title=Amprofon official twitter|publisher= |language=Spanish |accessdate=2014-01-30</ref>

